<TITLE> Media enjoys freedom: PM </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 3 (bdnews24.com)- Reaffirming her administration's commitment towards freedom of expression, prime minister Sheikh Hasina has said the media in Bangladesh enjoys freedom. The prime minister made the remark when US ambassador to Bangladesh James F Moriarty called on her, her press secretary Abul Kalam Azad said on Thursday. The prime minister's comments came amid criticism by opposition political parties that the government was gagging the media by closing BNP-leaning Bengali-language newspaper Amar Desh and blocking social networking website Facebook. The government temporarily shut the site on Saturday after a man posted caricatures of the prime minister and opposition leader Khaleda Zia and obnoxious comments. It closed the daily on charges of violation of publication agreement. Hasina urged for more US investment in Bangladesh's and greater cooperation in the power and energy sectors. Azad at a press briefing told reporters that the two discussed different bilateral issues on trade expansion. "In the meeting Hasina said her government was working tirelessly to ensure good governance through establishing human rights and upholding democratic values and the right to freedom of expression," the press secretary said. Citing the government's tough stance against terrorism and militancy, the prime minister said her administration is taking a slew of measures to curb terrorism in the greater national interest. She expressed at the human rights situation in Bangladesh and said her government was putting great emphasis on religious harmony. Ambassador-at-large Muhammad Ziauddin and secretary to the Prime Minister's Office Mollah Wahiduzzaman were attended the meeting bdn
